#1 Colon cancer
We had a fairly extensive discussion today with Mrs. Metcalf and her family in regard to her diagnosis and our treatment recommendations.  Currently, at this time, it appears she at least has a T4, N1 tumor and could have metastatic lesions in the lung as well.  We do not have a prior CT-scan to compare with and see if these are stable in nature or increasing in size.  Per the size that is listed on the previous scan in 2008, the size has increased; but once again, it would be very important to review the imaging studies in comparison to each other.  We would also like the patient to visit with the Colorectal Surgery team for resection of her primary mass in the ascending colon.  If she does not have likely metastatic disease in her lungs, then this will be for staging purposes as well as for primary treatment.  If does have metastatic disease in her lungs, then this will be for palliative intent so as to reduce the risk of complications down the line from this primary mass involving the abdominal wall.  The patient is in agreement, and we will have her visit with Dr. West later this afternoon.  Otherwise, we will be waiting on her outside CT-scan to arrive as well as her outside pathology reports.  Once we have all of this information, then we will be able to provider further treatment recommendations.  The patient is agreeable, and we otherwise answered all of her questions today.  The patient does have my card.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at Buffalo City County Hospital.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

