[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Metcalf is a very pleasant 78-year-old female from 29690 Bausman whose oncologic history is as follows:
1.  April 2010, the patient began noticing right lower quadrant pain that was dull in nature.  She brought this up with her PCP who eventually did a CT-scan showing a mass in the ascending colon.  She was then referred to the Anna Sundermann
2.  June 3, 2010, colonoscopy revealed a mass in the cecal area and ascending colon with a necrotic ulcer around the cecum.  Pathology from this mass showed a poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma.  Additionally, she had a CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis on that day which showed concerning bilateral pulmonary nodules and also likely benign liver lesions.  Additionally, it did show the primary tumor in the ascending colon, possibly involving the abdominal wall.
Mrs. Metcalf presents to us today for treatment recommendations in regard to her colon cancer.  She has been seen by Dr. Dana Butler at the Green Hospital in regard to this diagnosis thus far.  Dr. Butler has recommended palliative chemotherapy for her as she likely has metastatic disease due to the pulmonary nodules.  The patient is coming here for a second opinion.  Additionally, the patient brings records from a CT-scan in 2008 mentioning some pulmonary nodules at that time; however, she does not have the CD with the images for comparison.  Dr. Butler also did not have these available during his evaluation.  The patient otherwise is doing well with minimal complaints.  She does have some continued right lower quadrant abdominal pain, but this is not too severe in nature.  She denies any significant nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, blood in stool, or blood in urine.  She denies other issues such as fever, chills, sweats, chest pain, shortness-of-breath, cough, or urinary complaints.
The patient's ECOG performance status today is approximately a 0 to 1 as she is otherwise very healthy and has been working on her farm for the past 50+ years.  Her appetite is doing well.

